The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, February 13, 2004 				 Firms smell cash at global food fair
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Feb. 12: With Indias food and hospitality industry growing faster by the day, Food and Hotel Asia 2004, to be held in Singapore, seems to be just the right place to be in.																								Come April, Asias largest biennial international event for the food and hospitality sector will set the stage for Indian food and hospitality chains to reinforce their presence abroad.																								The four-day mega event will see some prominent Indian names participate in the exhibition. These include Agricultural and Processed Food Products Export Development Authority (APEDA), United Breweries Group, Bajaj Foods Limited, Bhalaria Metal Craft, Continental Equipment India, R amp;D Engineers, Satnam Overseas Limited, Shruti Industries India and Western Refrigeration.																								Tarun Bajaj, deputy general manager of APEDA, said, Indian companies should move quickly to take advantage of growing Asian food markets. FHA is a proven platform for Indian companies to launch their products in the international market.																								With liquor brands like Kingfisher premium lager beer, McDowells and Herbertsons range of spirits planning to expand in the far and south-east Asian region, Deepak Anand, president of UB Global Corp, said, Leveraging on the platform of FHA 2004, which will see 2,800 companies from over 60 countries, we hope to expand our presence in the region and create greater exposure for Indian products.																								According to a research conducted by Euromonitor International, Indias consumer expenditure on food is projected to increase by 8.3 per cent in the next two years reaching $170.68 million by 2006.																								FHA 2004 will feature more than 40 group pavilions from countries such as Australia, France, Germany, Italy, Korea, Taiwan and Thailand. 
